onseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior cerebral arteries, middle cerebral arteries, vertebral arteries, basilar artery, posterior cerebral arteries","Internal carotid arteries, external carotid arteries, vertebral arteries, basilar artery, posterior cerebral arteries","Anterior cerebral arteries, anterior communicating artery, internal carotid arteries, posterior communicating arteries, posterior cerebral arteries","Anterior cerebral arteries, middle cerebral arteries, internal carotid arteries, external carotid arteries, vertebral arteries","Middle cerebral arteries, anterior communicating artery, internal carotid arteries, posterior communicating arteries, basilar artery"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe arterial circle at the base of the brain consists of the \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior cerebral arteries, anterior communicating artery, internal carotid arteries, posterior communicating arteries, and posterior cerebral arteries (Image)\u003C/strong\u003E. These vessels form a complete ring that enables blood to be redirected if flow through any component is compromised.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe following vessels are not part of the Circle of Willis:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMiddle cerebral arteries\u003C/strong\u003E - have no contribution to the Circle of Willis \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVertebral arteries\u003C/strong\u003E - feed into the Circle of Willis, but are not a part of it\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasilar artery - \u003C/strong\u003Efeed into the Circle of Willis, but are not a part of it\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExternal carotid arteries \u003C/strong\u003E- have no contribution to the Circle of Willis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis arrangement allows for redundancy in cerebral blood supply, protecting against ischaemia if one vessel becomes occluded.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Circle of Willis is formed by anastomoses between the internal carotid and vertebrobasilar arterial systems at the base of the brain.","The anterior communicating artery connects the left and right anterior cerebral arteries.","The posterior communicating arteries connect the internal carotid arteries to the posterior cerebral arteries."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u0022Circle of Willis\u0022 by Anatomist90 is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons\u00a0Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported\u00a0license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/) \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Circle_of_Willis_5.jpg\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64032"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17333"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21301"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21301"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/jKCIDWSwQykZ8mpf18hppCnHMMkPmt.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/jKCIDWSwQykZ8mpf18hppCnHMMkPmt.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64032"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T08:46:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T08:47:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10023"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78689"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,